==English==

===Etymology===
Earlier {{m|en|seise}}, from {{inh|en|enm|seisen}}, {{m|enm|sesen}}, {{m|enm|saisen}}, from {{bor|en|fro|seisir||to take possession of; invest (person, court)}}, from {{der|en|ML.|sacīre||to lay claim to, appropriate}} (8th century) in the phrase {{m|la||ad propriam sacire}}, from Old Low {{bor|en|frk|*sakjan||to sue, bring legal action}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*sakjaną}}, {{m|gem-pro|*sakōną}} (compare {{cog|ang|sacian||to strive, brawl}}), from {{der|en|gem-pro|*sakaną}} (compare {{cog|osx|sakan||to accuse}}, {{cog|goh|sahhan||to bicker, quarrel, rebuke}}, {{cog|ang|sacan||to quarrel, claim by law, accuse}}.<ref>C.T. Onions, ed., Oxford Dictionary of English Etymology, s.v. "seize" (Oxford: Clarendon Press, 1996), 807.</ref> Cognate to {{m|en|sake}} and {{cog|la|sagio||to perceive acutely}}.

